USArrest_PCA_example

10/10/2019

PCA Example on US Arrest data

This is making use of a built in example data set USArrests

data(USArrests)
head(USArrests)
##            Murder Assault UrbanPop Rape
## Alabama      13.2     236       58 21.2
## Alaska       10.0     263       48 44.5
## Arizona       8.1     294       80 31.0
## Arkansas      8.8     190       50 19.5
## California    9.0     276       91 40.6
## Colorado      7.9     204       78 38.7

We we will scale or standardize the data. In scaling, we subtract the mean and divide by the standard deviation so the variables all have mean of zero and stddeve=1

This is done because of the wide variation in the scale of measurement

scArrests=apply(USArrests,2,scale)
mean(scArrests)
## [1] -7.739713e-17
sd(scArrests)
## [1] 0.9924337
head(scArrests)
##          Murder   Assault   UrbanPop         Rape
## [1,] 1.24256408 0.7828393 -0.5209066 -0.003416473
## [2,] 0.50786248 1.1068225 -1.2117642  2.484202941
## [3,] 0.07163341 1.4788032  0.9989801  1.042878388
## [4,] 0.23234938 0.2308680 -1.0735927 -0.184916602
## [5,] 0.27826823 1.2628144  1.7589234  2.067820292
## [6,] 0.02571456 0.3988593  0.8608085  1.864967207

Note that the var-cov matrix of the scaled data is actually now a correlation matrix

We can now run the PCA

z2=prcomp(USArrests,scale=TRUE)
summary(z2)
## Importance of components:
##                           PC1    PC2     PC3     PC4
## Standard deviation     1.5749 0.9949 0.59713 0.41645
## Proportion of Variance 0.6201 0.2474 0.08914 0.04336
## Cumulative Proportion  0.6201 0.8675 0.95664 1.00000

Lets plot the first two PCA axes scores

require(ggplot2)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
State<-rownames(USArrests)
PC1=z2$x[,1]
PC2=z2$x[,2]
PC3=z2$x[,3]
PC4=z2$x[,4]
myScores=data.frame(PC1=PC1,PC2=PC2,PC3=PC3,PC4=PC4)

#quartz()
#windows()
print(z2$rotation)
##                 PC1        PC2        PC3         PC4
## Murder   -0.5358995  0.4181809 -0.3412327  0.64922780
## Assault  -0.5831836  0.1879856 -0.2681484 -0.74340748
## UrbanPop -0.2781909 -0.8728062 -0.3780158  0.13387773
## Rape     -0.5434321 -0.1673186  0.8177779  0.08902432
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
barplot(z2$rotation[,1])
barplot(z2$rotation[,2])
barplot(z2$rotation[,3])
barplot(z2$rotation[,4])

barplot(z2$rotation[,1])

barplot(z2$rotation[,2])

p<-ggplot(myScores, aes(PC1,PC2)) + 
  modelr::geom_ref_line(h = 0) +
  modelr::geom_ref_line(v = 0) +
   geom_text(aes(label = State), size = 3) +
  xlab("First Principal Component") + 
  ylab("Second Principal Component") 

print(p)

x axis: murder,assault,rape; high left/low right y axis: urban population; high bottom/low top

Top right: low urban population, low murder,assault,rape Bottom right: high urban population, low murder,assauly,rape Bottom left: high urban population, high murder,assault,rape Top left: low urban population, high murder,assault,rape

barplot(z2$rotation[,3])

barplot(z2$rotation[,4])

Looking at cumulative varience explained PC1 and PC2 are the most.

p<-ggplot(myScores, aes(PC3,PC4)) + 
  modelr::geom_ref_line(h = 0) +
  modelr::geom_ref_line(v = 0) +
   geom_text(aes(label = State), size = 3) +
  xlab("Third Principal Component") + 
  ylab("Fourth Principal Component") 

print(p)

x axis: rape; low left/high right y axis: Murder,Assault; low murder;high assault;bottom/high murder;low assault;top

Top right: high rape/high murder;low assault Bottom right: high rape/low murder;high assault Bottom left: low rape/low murder;high assault Top left: low rape/high murder;low assault

pr.out=prcomp(USArrests,scale=TRUE)
pr.out$rotation
##                 PC1        PC2        PC3         PC4
## Murder   -0.5358995  0.4181809 -0.3412327  0.64922780
## Assault  -0.5831836  0.1879856 -0.2681484 -0.74340748
## UrbanPop -0.2781909 -0.8728062 -0.3780158  0.13387773
## Rape     -0.5434321 -0.1673186  0.8177779  0.08902432
biplot(pr.out, scale=0)

pr.out$rotation=-pr.out$rotation
pr.out$x=-pr.out$x
plot1 <- biplot(pr.out,scale=0)

plot1
